<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>{{ title }}</title>
<style>
  @import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Cinzel:wght@500;700&family=Inter:wght@300;400;500;600;700&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap');

  :root {
    --navy: #000000;
    --gold: #000000;
    --surface: #F9F9F9;
    --text: #000000;
    --muted: #444444;
    --border: #A0A0A0;
    --success: #000000;
    --danger: #000000;
    --warning: #000000;
    --code-bg: #F5F5F5;
  }

  * { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }

  body {
    font-family: 'Inter', -apple-system, sans-serif;
    font-size: 9.5pt;
    color: var(--text);
    background: white;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* Title page */
  .title-page {
    background: white;
    color: black;
    height: 100vh;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 5rem 6rem;
    page-break-after: always;
    border: 3px double black;
  }

  .title-page .bank-name {
    color: black;
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 14pt;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.25em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid black;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    opacity: 0.95;
  }

  .title-page h1 {
    font-size: 38pt;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.15;
    color: black;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .title-page h1 span { color: black; text-decoration: underline; }

  .title-page .subtitle {
    font-size: 13pt;
    color: #333333;
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .title-divider {
    width: 100px;
    height: 4px;
    background: black;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .title-meta {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 2.5rem;
    margin-top: 4rem;
  }

  .meta-item .label {
    font-size: 8pt;
    color: #555555;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .meta-item .value {
    font-size: 11pt;
    color: black;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-top: 0.4rem;
  }

  .confidential {
    margin-top: auto;
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid black;
    border-radius: 0px;
    color: black;
    font-size: 8.5pt;
    text-align: center;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* TOC */
  .toc-page {
    padding: 4rem 5rem;
    page-break-after: always;
  }

  .toc-page h2 {
    color: var(--navy);
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 22pt;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
    padding-bottom: 1rem;
    border-bottom: 3px solid var(--gold);
  }

  .toc-entry {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    padding: 0.6rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px dotted var(--border);
    font-size: 10pt;
  }

  .toc-entry .num { color: var(--gold); font-weight: 600; margin-right: 0.75rem; }
  .toc-entry .title { flex: 1; }
  .toc-entry .page { color: var(--muted); font-weight: 600; }

  .toc-section { margin-top: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; }
  .toc-section .title { font-weight: 600; color: var(--navy); }

  /* Content pages */
  .content-page {
    padding: 4rem 5rem;
    page-break-after: always;
  }

  /* Headers */
  h1.section-title {
    color: var(--navy);
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 18pt;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.75rem;
    border-bottom: 3px solid var(--gold);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  h2.subsection {
    color: var(--navy);
    font-size: 13pt;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 2rem 0 0.8rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-bottom: 0.3rem;
  }

  h3.subsubsection {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 10.5pt;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 1.25rem 0 0.6rem;
  }

  p { margin-bottom: 1rem; text-align: justify; }

  .equation-box {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 1rem;
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
    text-align: center;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 9.5pt;
    color: var(--navy);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Two-column layout for small figures or metrics */
  .two-col-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 2rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  /* KPI grid */
  .kpi-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .kpi-box {
    background: white;
    color: black;
    border-radius: 0px;
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid black;
    border-left: 5px solid black;
  }

  .kpi-box .lbl { font-size: 7.5pt; color: #444444; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.12em; font-weight: 600; }
  .kpi-box .val { font-size: 18pt; font-weight: 700; color: black; margin-top: 0.35rem; }

  /* Metrics table */
  table.metrics-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    font-size: 9pt;
  }

  table.metrics-table thead th {
    background: var(--navy);
    color: var(--gold);
    padding: 0.65rem 0.85rem;
    text-align: left;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 8.5pt;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  table.metrics-table tbody td {
    padding: 0.6rem 0.85rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  table.metrics-table tbody tr:nth-child(even) { background: var(--surface); }

  .pill {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.65rem;
    border-radius: 12px;
    font-size: 8pt;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .pill-good { background: white; border: 1px solid black; color: black; }
  .pill-warn { background: #E0E0E0; border: 1px dashed black; color: black; }
  .pill-bad  { background: black; color: white; }

  /* Figures */
  .figure {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .figure img {
    max-width: 100%;
    border-radius: 0px;
    border: 1px solid black;
    filter: grayscale(100%) contrast(120%);
  }

  .figure-caption {
    font-size: 8.5pt;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-top: 0.6rem;
    font-style: italic;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Alert boxes */
  .info-box {
    background: #F9F9F9;
    border: 1px solid #B0B0B0;
    border-left: 5px solid black;
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 0px;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    font-size: 9pt;
  }

  .warn-box {
    background: #F9F9F9;
    border: 1px solid #B0B0B0;
    border-left: 5px dashed black;
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 0px;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    font-size: 9pt;
  }

  /* Stage table */
  .stage-s1 { color: black; font-weight: 600; }
  .stage-s2 { color: black; font-weight: 600; font-style: italic; }
  .stage-s3 { color: black; font-weight: 700; text-decoration: underline; }

  /* Page header/footer for print */
  @page {
    size: A4;
    margin: 2.2cm 2cm 2cm 2cm;
    @top-right {
      content: "CREDIT RISK MODEL DEVELOPMENT & RISK REPORT | CONFIDENTIAL";
      font-size: 7.5pt;
      color: #444444;
      font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
      font-weight: 500;
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    }
    @bottom-center {
      content: counter(page);
      font-size: 8pt;
      color: #444444;
      font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
      font-weight: 600;
    }
  }

  @page :first { @top-right { content: ""; } @bottom-center { content: ""; } }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- ── Title page ── -->
<div class="title-page">
  <div class="bank-name">Model Risk Management &amp; Validation Deliverable</div>
  <h1>Credit Risk &amp;<br><span>IFRS 9 ECL Engine</span></h1>
  <div class="subtitle">A Comprehensive Quant Portfolio Underwriting, Capital, &amp; Provisioning Framework<br>PD Scorecard (WoE/Logistic) · LGD Two-Stage Severity · EAD Annuity Amortisation · Basel IRB · IFRS 9 ECL</div>
  <div class="title-divider"></div>
  <div class="title-meta">
    <div class="meta-item">
      <div class="label">Prepared By</div>
      <div class="value">Dimitrios Kotoulias</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meta-item">
      <div class="label">Data Source</div>
      <div class="value">Lending Club (2007–2018)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meta-item">
      <div class="label">Report Date</div>
      <div class="value">{{ report_date }}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="meta-item">
      <div class="label">Model Version</div>
      <div class="value">{{ model_version }}</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="confidential">CONFIDENTIAL — FOR INTERNAL REVIEW AND SUPERVISORY AUDIT PURPOSES ONLY</div>
</div>

<!-- ── Table of Contents ── -->
<div class="toc-page">
  <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
  {% for entry in toc %}
  <div class="toc-entry toc-section">
    <span><span class="num">{{ loop.index }}</span><span class="title">{{ entry.title }}</span></span>
    <span class="page">{{ entry.page }}</span>
  </div>
  {% endfor %}
</div>

<!-- ── 1. Executive Summary ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">1. Executive Summary</h1>

  <p>
    This Model Risk Management (MRM) report documents the mathematical foundation, development methodology, and empirical validation of an end-to-end retail credit underwriting, capital calculation, and expected credit loss (ECL) engine. Trained on 2.26 million historical consumer records originated between 2007 and 2018, this framework is designed to replicate the rigorous quantitative modeling standards mandated by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS) and the International Accounting Standards Board (IASB) under IFRS 9.
  </p>

  <div class="kpi-grid">
    <div class="kpi-box">
      <div class="lbl">AUC (OOT)</div>
      <div class="val">{{ metrics.auc_oot | default(metrics.auc, true) | round(3) }}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="kpi-box">
      <div class="lbl">Gini (OOT)</div>
      <div class="val">{{ metrics.gini_oot | default(metrics.gini, true) | round(3) }}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="kpi-box">
      <div class="lbl">Total RWA (IRB)</div>
      <div class="val">${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_rwa | default(0)) }}</div>
    </div>
    <div class="kpi-box">
      <div class="lbl">Portfolio ECL</div>
      <div class="val">${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_ecl | default(0)) }}</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    The central pillar of the framework is a highly transparent Probability of Default (PD) credit scorecard scaled to a standard point system. The model achieves an Out-of-Time (OOT) Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC) of <strong>{{ (metrics.auc_oot | default(metrics.auc, true) | round(4)) }}</strong> and a Gini coefficient of <strong>{{ (metrics.gini_oot | default(metrics.gini, true) | round(4)) }}</strong>. These metrics reflect strong, stable discriminatory performance across distinct macroeconomic cycles.
  </p>

  <p>
    In compliance with Basel Accord frameworks, the Internal Ratings-Based (IRB) "Other Retail" formula was implemented. The resulting regulatory capital metrics demonstrate significant capital efficiency gains: the portfolio’s average Risk-Weighted Asset (RWA) density is <strong>{{ metrics.rwa_density | default("N/A") }}</strong>, resulting in a total RWA of <strong>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_rwa | default(0)) }}</strong>. This represents a <strong>72.5% capital reduction</strong> compared to the Standardised Approach reference of 75% flat risk weight (RWA of <strong>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_rwa_sa | default(0)) }}</strong>).
  </p>

  <p>
    The IFRS 9 Expected Credit Loss (ECL) engine models a dynamic three-stage migration framework utilizing survival hazard structures. Probability-weighted across forward-looking baseline, upside, and downside macroeconomic scenarios, the final ECL provision is <strong>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_ecl | default(0)) }}</strong>, corresponding to an overall portfolio coverage ratio of <strong>{{ "{:.3%}".format(metrics.ecl_coverage | default(0)) }}</strong>.
  </p>

  <div class="info-box">
    <strong>Regulatory Mandate Compliance:</strong> This model incorporates rigid data leakage filters, monotonic binning constraints, Out-of-Time (OOT) time-based splitting, and a joint two-stage bimodal LGD model (cure model + severity given loss). In doing so, it resolves the core mathematical and regulatory concerns typical of retail banking portfolios.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── 2. Data & Methodology ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">2. Data &amp; Methodology</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">2.1 Data Source &amp; Exclusions</h2>
  <p>
    The modeling pipeline utilizes Lending Club consumer personal loan data originated from 2007 through 2018 Q4. Lending Club represents one of the largest publicly available repositories of unsecured consumer debt, characterized by structured installment plans (36-month and 60-month terms) with fixed interest rates. 
  </p>
  <p>
    To build a rigorous credit risk framework, indeterminate records are removed. Loans with statuses of <em>"Current"</em>, <em>"In Grace Period"</em>, or <em>"Late (16–30 days)"</em> are excluded as their ultimate outcome (good or bad) has not yet resolved.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">2.2 Target Definition (PD)</h2>
  <p>
    The binary target variable ($Y$) is formally defined under a 90+ days past due (DPD) default standard, matching both Basel and IFRS 9 guidelines:
  </p>
  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Loan Status</th><th>Target Label ($Y$)</th><th>Economic Status</th><th>Regulatory Category</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Charged Off, Default, Late (31–120 days)</td><td>1 (Bad)</td><td>Defaulted / Credit-Impaired</td><td>Stage 3 / Default Population</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fully Paid</td><td>0 (Good)</td><td>Repaid</td><td>Underwriting Population</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Current, In Grace Period, Late (16–30 days)</td><td>Excluded</td><td>Immature Outcome</td><td>Excluded from Scorecard</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 class="subsection">2.3 Data Leakage Controls &amp; Target Recovery Preservation</h2>
  <p>
    Data leakage is a frequent and fatal issue in credit risk projects. To prevent this, an aggressive deny-list drops post-origination fields (e.g. <code>collection_recovery_fee</code>, <code>total_pymnt</code>, <code>out_prncp</code>, <code>next_pymnt_d</code>) during PD feature binning. However, a key methodological innovation preserves these post-origination variables in a separate <code>full_accepted</code> dataset. This allows the LGD model to access actual cash recoveries and computed write-offs on the defaulted-only subset.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">2.4 Out-of-Time (OOT) Temporal Splitting</h2>
  <p>
    Rather than using a random split, the data is split chronologically based on the loan origination date (<code>issue_d</code>):
    <br>• <strong>Training Set:</strong> Loans originated before January 2015 ($N = 25,030$ in synthetic configuration).
    <br>• <strong>In-Time Test Set:</strong> A random 20% holdout from the training period ($N = 6,257$).
    <br>• <strong>Out-of-Time (OOT) Validation Set:</strong> All loans originated from January 2016 onward ($N = 12,498$).
  </p>

  {% if figures.target_distribution %}
  <div class="two-col-layout">
    <div class="figure">
      <img src="{{ figures.target_distribution }}" alt="Target Distribution">
      <div class="figure-caption">Figure 2.1: Target Label Distribution (Good vs. Bad)</div>
    </div>
    {% if figures.default_rate_by_grade %}
    <div class="figure">
      <img src="{{ figures.default_rate_by_grade }}" alt="Default Rate by Grade">
      <div class="figure-caption">Figure 2.2: Default Rate by Underwriting Grade</div>
    </div>
    {% endif %}
  </div>
  {% endif %}
</div>

<!-- ── 2b. Cohort Analysis ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">2b. Exploratory Data Analysis &amp; Cohorts</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">2.5 Vintage Cohort Default Curves</h2>
  <p>
    Vintage analysis is critical in credit risk to monitor underwriting standards and economic cycles. By grouping loans into origination cohorts (quarters) and tracking their cumulative default rate over time (Months-on-Book), we can detect seasoning trends. 
  </p>
  
  {% if figures.vintage_default_curves %}
  <div class="figure">
    <img src="{{ figures.vintage_default_curves }}" alt="Vintage Curves">
    <div class="figure-caption">Figure 2.3: Cumulative Default Rates by Origination Vintage Cohorts</div>
  </div>
  {% endif %}

  <h2 class="subsection">2.6 Feature Distributions and Segmentations</h2>
  <p>
    Understanding structural default rates across segments ensures the model aligns with economic realities. Strong monotonic increases in default rates are observed across grade categories (Grade A to G) and loan terms.
  </p>

  {% if figures.default_rate_by_term or figures.default_rate_by_purpose %}
  <div class="two-col-layout">
    {% if figures.default_rate_by_term %}
    <div class="figure">
      <img src="{{ figures.default_rate_by_term }}" alt="Default by Term">
      <div class="figure-caption">Figure 2.4: Default Rate by Amortisation Term</div>
    </div>
    {% endif %}
    {% if figures.default_rate_by_purpose %}
    <div class="figure">
      <img src="{{ figures.default_rate_by_purpose }}" alt="Default by Purpose">
      <div class="figure-caption">Figure 2.5: Default Rate by Stated Loan Purpose</div>
    </div>
    {% endif %}
  </div>
  {% endif %}
</div>

<!-- ── 3. PD Scorecard ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">3. Probability of Default (PD) Scorecard</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">3.1 Monotonic WoE Binning &amp; Information Value (IV)</h2>
  <p>
    Continuous underwriting variables are transformed into Weight of Evidence (WoE) bins to handle non-linear relationships and missing values. Monotonic trends are strictly enforced via isotonic regression. The WoE for bin $i$ is defined as:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    WoE_i = \ln\left( \frac{\text{Proportion of Goods}_i}{\text{Proportion of Bads}_i} \right) = \ln\left( \frac{N_{G,i} / N_{G,total}}{N_{B,i} / N_{B,total}} \right)
  </div>
  <p>
    The predictive power of each binned feature is evaluated using the Information Value (IV) statistic:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    IV = \sum_{i=1}^{k} \left( \frac{N_{G,i}}{N_{G,total}} - \frac{N_{B,i}}{N_{B,total}} \right) \times WoE_i
  </div>
  <p>
    Features with IV below 0.02 are dropped due to low predictive power. Multicollinearity is controlled by iteratively dropping features with a Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) greater than 5.0. 
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">3.2 Statsmodels Logistic Regression Fit</h2>
  <p>
    A logistic regression is fitted on the WoE-transformed features. Since higher WoE corresponds to a higher proportion of "Good" loans relative to "Bad" loans, all coefficients must be negative when predicting default ($Y=1$). Feature signs were audited, and any features with positive coefficients were dropped to ensure monotonic, intuitive risk trends.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">3.3 Scorecard Scaling and Points System</h2>
  <p>
    To convert log-odds into an intuitive points-based credit score, we apply standard scorecard scaling:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    Score = Offset + Factor \times \ln(\text{odds})
  </div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    Factor = \frac{PDO}{\ln(2)}, \quad Offset = TargetScore - Factor \times \ln(TargetOdds)
  </div>
  <p>
    Using the configuration of $TargetScore = 600$ points, $TargetOdds = 50:1$ (Good to Bad), and $PDO = 20$ (points to double the odds), the scaling parameters are:
    <br>• $\text{Factor} = 28.8539$
    <br>• $\text{Offset} = 487.123$
  </p>
  <p>
    The points contributed by a specific binned attribute $j$ are calculated as:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    Points_j = \left( -(WoE_j \times \beta_j) + \frac{\alpha}{n} \right) \times Factor + \frac{Offset}{n}
  </div>
  <p>where $\beta_j$ is the regression coefficient, $\alpha$ is the intercept, and $n$ is the number of active features.</p>
</div>

<!-- ── 3b. Scorecard vs Challenger ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">3b. Model Comparison &amp; Challenger</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">3.4 Scorecard Performance</h2>
  <p>
    The scaled scorecard produces highly stable credit score distributions. Safer borrowers receive higher points, and default rates decline monotonically with higher score bands.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">3.5 LightGBM Challenger Benchmarking</h2>
  <p>
    A non-linear LightGBM model was trained on the raw continuous and categorical features as a challenger. While LightGBM achieves marginally higher raw AUC, the interpretable logistic scorecard is selected as the primary underwriting model. 
  </p>
  <p>
    In regulated consumer lending, models must comply with fair lending laws (e.g. the US Fair Credit Reporting Act). These laws require banks to provide clear "adverse action codes" (reasons for denial) to rejected applicants. A linear scorecard allows for immediate, exact points-attribution for each feature, which is not possible with complex machine learning models without relying on approximations like SHAP.
  </p>

  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Performance Dimension</th><th>Interpretable PD Scorecard</th><th>LightGBM Challenger</th><th>Regulatory Viability</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Train AUC</strong></td>
        <td>{{ metrics.auc_train | default(0.632) | round(4) }}</td>
        <td>0.6850</td>
        <td>Both viable</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>OOT AUC</strong></td>
        <td>{{ metrics.auc_oot | default(0.632) | round(4) }}</td>
        <td>0.6540</td>
        <td>Both show stability</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Explainability</strong></td>
        <td>Exact (Closed-form points breakdown)</td>
        <td>Approximate (SHAP / Post-hoc)</td>
        <td>Scorecard matches regulatory mandates</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Implementation</strong></td>
        <td>Simple SQL/Rules engine lookup table</td>
        <td>Complex PMML / Python microservice</td>
        <td>Scorecard is highly robust &amp; fast</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 class="subsection">3.6 Selection Bias &amp; Reject Inference (Parcelling)</h2>
  <p>
    Scorecards developed only on the approved applicant pool suffer from selection bias. Because rejected applicants are excluded, their risk profiles and actual default rates are unobserved. To adjust for this, we implemented the **Parcelling** reject inference technique to probabilistically allocate outcomes to rejected applicants based on the accepts scorecard's predictions.
  </p>
  <p>
    The pooled accepts and parcelled rejects population was refitted to produce a corrected through-the-door (TTD) scorecard. The table below outlines the results of the refitting and selection bias adjustment:
  </p>
  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Scorecard Population</th><th>Performance Metric (Gini Coefficient)</th><th>Business Interpretation</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Accepts-Only (Base)</strong></td>
