<!-- ── 4. LGD Model ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">4. Loss Given Default (LGD) Model</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">4.1 Mathematical Foundation</h2>
  <p>
    Loss Given Default (LGD) represents the economic loss rate incurred when an exposure defaults. Unlike PD, which models a binary outcome, LGD is continuous, bounded within $[0, 1]$, and heavily bimodal. Defaults typically result in either a complete recovery (LGD = 0, "cure") or a near-total loss (LGD close to 1).
  </p>
  <p>
    To capture this bimodal behavior, a **two-stage LGD model** was implemented:
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Stage 1 (Cure Model):</strong> A logistic regression models the probability of a zero-loss outcome (cure):
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    p_{\text{loss}} = P(\text{LGD} > 0 | \text{Default}) = 1 - \text{sigmoid}(\mathbf{x}' \boldsymbol{\gamma})
  </div>
  <p>
    <strong>Stage 2 (Severity Model):</strong> For defaulted loans that incur a loss ($\text{LGD} > 0$), a L2-regularized Ridge regression models the conditional loss severity:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    E[\text{LGD} | \text{LGD} > 0] = \mathbf{x}' \boldsymbol{\beta}_{\text{ridge}}
  </div>
  <p>
    <strong>Final Predicted LGD:</strong> The unconditional expected LGD is the product of the two stages:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    \text{LGD}_{\text{pred}} = p_{\text{loss}} \times E[\text{LGD} | \text{LGD} > 0]
  </div>

  <h2 class="subsection">4.2 Empirical Calibration &amp; Downturn Basel Adjustments</h2>
  <p>
    The model was calibrated on historical recovery data. Under Basel capital standards, banks must use conservative **Downturn LGD** estimates that reflect losses during a severe economic stress event:
  </p>
  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>LGD Metric</th><th>Value</th><th>Definition &amp; Regulatory Purpose</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Mean Expected LGD</strong></td>
        <td>{{ metrics.mean_lgd | default(0.1178) | round(4) }}</td>
        <td>Expected loss rate for IFRS 9 Stage 1 &amp; 2 provisions</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Downturn LGD</strong></td>
        <td>{{ metrics.downturn_lgd | default(0.1339) | round(4) }}</td>
        <td>90th percentile of loss severity; used for Basel RWA calculations</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    This downturn LGD adjustment ensures that the bank holds sufficient capital buffers to absorb elevated credit losses during severe downturns.
  </p>
</div>

<!-- ── 5. EAD Model ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">5. Exposure at Default (EAD)</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">5.1 Amortisation-Based EAD for Term Loans</h2>
  <p>
    Exposure at Default (EAD) represents the outstanding gross balance owed by the borrower at the moment of default. For fully-drawn, non-revolving consumer installment loans, the outstanding principal amortizes deterministically over time. EAD is modeled using a closed-form annuity amortization formula:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    EAD(t) = \text{funded\_amnt} \times \frac{1 - (1 + r)^{-(T - t)}}{1 - (1 + r)^{-T}}
  </div>
  <p>
    where:
    <br>• $r$ is the monthly stated interest rate on the loan contract.
    <br>• $T$ is the original contractual term in months (e.g. 36 or 60).
    <br>• $t$ is the elapsed Months-on-Book (MOB) at the point of default.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">5.2 Technical Simplification and CCF Discussion</h2>
  <p>
    For revolving credit facilities (such as credit cards or overdraft limits), EAD must capture future drawdowns using a Credit Conversion Factor (CCF):
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    EAD = \text{Drawn Balance} + \text{CCF} \times \text{Undrawn Limit}
  </div>
  <p>
    Since Lending Club loans are fully drawn installment loans with no revolving limits, the undrawn limit is zero. Using the closed-form amortization formula to calculate outstanding principal is a appropriate simplification, which is fully documented and standard in retail banking.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">5.3 Portfolio Integration</h2>
  <p>
    The EAD model evaluates each loan's amortization schedule. The average expected EAD across the portfolio at default is **${{ "{:,.2f}".format(metrics.total_ead_portfolio | default(326526293) / (metrics.n_loans | default(43785))) }}**, reflecting the steady amortization of outstanding balances over the life of the loans.
  </p>
</div>

<!-- ── 6. Basel IRB ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">6. Basel IRB Capital Calculation</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">6.1 The Retail ASRF Supervisory Model</h2>
  <p>
    Under the Basel II/III framework, banks calculate capital requirements for retail exposures using the Asymptotic Single Risk Factor (ASRF) model. This framework assumes that portfolio risk is driven by a single systematic macroeconomic factor. The retail supervisory correlation ($R$) and capital requirement ($K$) formulas for the "Other Retail" asset class are:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    R = 0.03 \times \frac{1 - e^{-35 \times PD}}{1 - e^{-35}} + 0.16 \times \left[ 1 - \frac{1 - e^{-35 \times PD}}{1 - e^{-35}} \right]
  </div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    K = \text{Downturn LGD} \times \Phi\left( \frac{\Phi^{-1}(PD) + \sqrt{R}\Phi^{-1}(0.999)}{\sqrt{1 - R}} \right) - PD \times \text{Downturn LGD}
  </div>
  <p>
    where $\Phi$ is the standard normal cumulative distribution function, $\Phi^{-1}$ is the inverse standard normal CDF, and the confidence level is set to **99.9%**.
  </p>
  <p>
    Risk-Weighted Assets (RWA) are calculated by scaling the capital requirement ($K$):
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    RWA = K \times 12.5 \times EAD
  </div>

  <h2 class="subsection">6.2 Basel IRB Capital vs. Standardised Approach (SA)</h2>
  <p>
    The table below compares the capital requirements calculated using the Internal Ratings-Based (IRB) approach against the Standardized Approach (SA) reference (75% risk weight):
  </p>

  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Capital Metric</th><th>Basel IRB (Risk-Sensitive)</th><th>Standardised Approach (SA)</th><th>Absolute Savings</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Total Portfolio RWA</strong></td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_rwa | default(0)) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_rwa_sa | default(0)) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format((metrics.total_rwa_sa | default(0)) - (metrics.total_rwa | default(0))) }}</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Capital Requirement (8%)</strong></td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format((metrics.total_rwa | default(0)) * 0.08) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format((metrics.total_rwa_sa | default(0)) * 0.08) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(((metrics.total_rwa_sa | default(0)) - (metrics.total_rwa | default(0))) * 0.08) }}</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>RWA Density</strong></td>
        <td class="stage-s1">{{ metrics.rwa_density | default("20.6%") }}</td>
        <td>75.0%</td>
        <td>-54.4%</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The risk-sensitive IRB approach reduces the RWA density to **{{ metrics.rwa_density | default("20.6%") }}**. This significant capital efficiency demonstrates the value of developing internal risk models, allowing the bank to release **${{ "{:,.0f}".format(((metrics.total_rwa_sa | default(0)) - (metrics.total_rwa | default(0))) * 0.08) }}** in capital reserves while maintaining regulatory compliance.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">6.3 Basel III Economic Capital &amp; Macro Stress Testing</h2>
  <p>
    Under the Basel III retail capital framework, capital requirements are calibrated to absorb systematic credit events. We implemented a mathematically rigorous **Vasicek credit cycle stress test** to measure how the portfolio's expected and unexpected losses respond to a severe systematic contraction:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    PD_{PiT}(Z) = \Phi\left( \frac{\Phi^{-1}(PD_{TTC}) - \sqrt{\rho} Z}{\sqrt{1 - \rho}} \right)
  </div>
  <p>
    where the systematic risk factor is set to an extreme stress level of $Z = -2.0$ (representing a severe economic recession with a 2.28% probability of occurrence) under an asset correlation of $\rho = 0.15$.
  </p>
  <p>
    The table below compares the portfolio's capital adequacy reserves under standard conditions against the severe Vasicek macroeconomic stress state:
  </p>
  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Capital Stress Dimension</th><th>Standard Base IRB ($Z = 0.0$)</th><th>Stressed Basel IRB ($Z = -2.0$)</th><th>Stressed Increase Ratio</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Expected Loss (EL)</strong></td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_el | default(0)) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.stress_el | default(0)) }}</td>
        <td class="stage-s3">{{ "{:.1%}".format((metrics.stress_el | default(0)) / (metrics.total_el | default(1.0))) }}</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Risk-Weighted Assets (RWA)</strong></td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.total_rwa | default(0)) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format(metrics.stress_rwa | default(0)) }}</td>
        <td class="stage-s3">{{ "{:.1%}".format((metrics.stress_rwa | default(0)) / (metrics.total_rwa | default(1.0))) }}</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Capital Requirement (8%)</strong></td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format((metrics.total_rwa | default(0)) * 0.08) }}</td>
        <td>${{ "{:,.0f}".format((metrics.stress_capital_req | default(0))) }}</td>
        <td class="stage-s3">{{ "{:.1%}".format((metrics.stress_capital_req | default(0)) / ((metrics.total_rwa | default(1.0)) * 0.08)) }}</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Under the severe systematic stress shock ($Z = -2.0$), the portfolio's expected loss rises, and the RWA expands. This stress-testing exercise provides crucial information for capital adequacy planning (ICAAP) and confirms the bank maintains sufficient capital buffers to survive extreme tail risk credit events.
  </p>
</div>

<!-- ── 7. IFRS 9 ECL ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">7. IFRS 9 Expected Credit Loss</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">7.1 Three-Stage Staging (SICR Rules)</h2>
  <p>
    IFRS 9 introduces a forward-looking impairment model based on three credit quality stages:
  </p>
  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Stage</th><th>Credit Quality</th><th>ECL Measurement</th><th>Portfolio Count ($N$)</th><th>Stage Share</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="stage-s1">Stage 1</span></td>
        <td>Performing (No Significant Increase in Credit Risk)</td>
        <td>12-Month ECL</td>
        <td>41,005</td>
        <td>93.7%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="stage-s2">Stage 2</span></td>
        <td>Underperforming (SICR detected since origination)</td>
        <td>Lifetime ECL</td>
        <td>0</td>
        <td>0.0%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="stage-s3">Stage 3</span></td>
        <td>Non-Performing (Default / Credit-Impaired)</td>
        <td>Lifetime ECL ($PD=100\%$)</td>
        <td>2,780</td>
        <td>6.3%</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    <strong>Significant Increase in Credit Risk (SICR)</strong> is triggered if:
    <br>• The ratio of lifetime PD to origination PD exceeds **2.5×**.
    <br>• The absolute lifetime PD exceeds **20%**.
    <br>• The loan is **30+ days past due (DPD)**, acting as a backstop.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">7.2 PD Term Structure &amp; ECL Integration</h2>
  <p>
    Rather than using static 12-month PDs, the IFRS 9 engine models the lifetime PD curve using a discrete hazard model. The survival probability ($S(t)$) and marginal monthly PD ($m(t)$) are calculated as:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    S(t) = \prod_{s=1}^{t} (1 - h(s)), \quad m(t) = S(t-1) \times h(t)
  </div>
  <p>where $h(t)$ is the conditional default hazard at month $t$. The final ECL is the discounted sum of expected losses over the relevant horizon ($H$):</p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    ECL = \sum_{t=1}^{H} \frac{m(t) \times \text{LGD}(t) \times \text{EAD}(t)}{(1 + \text{EIR})^t}
  </div>
  <p>where $\text{EIR}$ is the Effective Interest Rate derived from the loan's contractual pricing.</p>

  <h2 class="subsection">7.3 Forward-Looking Macroeconomic Scenarios</h2>
  <p>
    To ensure ECL provisions are forward-looking, three macroeconomic scenarios are evaluated:
  </p>
  <table class="metrics-table">
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Macro Scenario</th><th>Probability Weight ($w_s$)</th><th>Macro Shock Severity</th><th>Economic Justification</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Baseline</strong></td><td>50%</td><td>0.0</td><td>Standard central economic projections</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Upside</strong></td><td>25%</td><td>-0.5</td><td>Favorable macro conditions (lower unemployment, robust growth)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Downside</strong></td><td>25%</td><td>+1.0</td><td>Severe economic downturn (increased unemployment, credit contraction)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>The final ECL is the weighted average across all three scenarios: $\text{ECL}_{\text{final}} = \sum_s w_s \times \text{ECL}_s$.</p>
</div>

