<!-- ── 9. Limitations ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">9. Limitations, Caveats &amp; Next Steps</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">9.1 Documented Simplifications</h2>
  <p>
    In accordance with Model Risk Management standards, all key simplifying assumptions made during development are documented:
    <br>• <strong>EAD Term Amortisation:</strong> Approximating EAD using the closed-form amortization formula is suitable for installment term loans but does not capture revolving exposures, which require Credit Conversion Factors (CCF).
    <br>• <strong>LGD Stage 2 Severity:</strong> The Stage 2 LGD severity model utilizes L2-regularized Ridge regression. While robust, future iterations could use beta regression or fractional logit GLMs to naturally bound predictions within $[0, 1]$.
    <br>• <strong>Macroeconomic Overlay:</strong> The forward-looking macro overlay uses a scalar log-odds scaling approach. Implementing a vector autoregressive (VAR) model linking historical default rates to specific macroeconomic variables (such as unemployment or GDP growth) would improve risk sensitivity.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">9.2 Model Risk &amp; Limitations</h2>
  <p>
    The Lending Club dataset is limited to US consumer loans and may not generalize to corporate lending, small-business loans, or other international retail portfolios. Additionally, the dataset excludes collateral details, meaning the LGD model relies primarily on underwriting grades and debt-to-income (DTI) metrics.
  </p>

  <h2 class="subsection">9.3 Recommended Next Steps</h2>
  <p>
    1. **Reject Inference Integration:** Apply reject inference techniques (such as hard cut-off augmentation or parcelling) on the rejected-loans dataset to adjust for selection bias in the underwriting population.
    2. **Independent Validation:** Conduct an independent review of the binning algorithms and scorecard points scaling to verify math and logical consistency.
    3. **Advanced LGD Modeling:** Explore survival-based LGD models that capture time-varying recovery patterns over the life of defaulted assets.
  </p>

  <div class="warn-box">
    <strong>Model Risk Statement:</strong> This credit risk model and IFRS 9 engine is a portfolio project designed for banking internships and independent validation exercises. It is not approved for live production underwriting or regulatory capital reporting.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── 10. Appendices ── -->
<div class="content-page">
  <h1 class="section-title">10. Appendices</h1>

  <h2 class="subsection">A. Scorecard Scaling Derivation</h2>
  <p>
    To map the log-odds predicted by the logistic regression to a scaled credit score, we solve the linear system:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    Score = Offset + Factor \times \ln(\text{odds})
  </div>
  <p>
    Subject to the boundary conditions:
    <br>• $\text{Score} = 600$ at $\text{odds} = 50:1$ ($\ln(50) \approx 3.912$)
    <br>• $\text{Score} = 620$ at $\text{odds} = 100:1$ ($\ln(100) \approx 4.605$, satisfying $\text{PDO} = 20$)
  </p>
  <p>
    Solving for the scaling parameters:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    Factor = \frac{20}{\ln(100) - \ln(50)} = \frac{20}{\ln(2)} \approx 28.8539
  </div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    Offset = 600 - 28.8539 \times \ln(50) \approx 487.123
  </div>

  <h2 class="subsection">B. Basel IRB "Other Retail" Supervisory Parameters</h2>
  <p>
    Under BCBS §322–328, the regulatory correlation ($R$) is constrained between $0.03$ and $0.16$. The correlation decays exponentially as the PD increases, reflecting the lower correlation of defaults among higher-risk borrowers during stable economic conditions:
  </p>
  <div class="equation-box">
    R = 0.03 \times \frac{1 - e^{-35 \times PD}}{1 - e^{-35}} + 0.16 \times \left[ 1 - \frac{1 - e^{-35 \times PD}}{1 - e^{-35}} \right]
  </div>
  <p>
    For the RWA calculation, the supervisory PD floor of **0.03%** is strictly applied to ensure a minimum capital charge.
  </p>

